ardees, and other acclaimed writers and thinkers debate the big questions: who we are, the nature of reality, science and religion, consciousness and materialism, and the mysteries of time. In so doing, they also inquire into how uniting experts from different areas of study to consider these topics might help us address the existential risks we face today. Convened and moderated by the physicist and author Marcelo Gleiser, these public dialogues model constructive engagement between the sciences and the humanities—and show why intellectual cooperation is necessary to shape our collective future.Contributors include David Chalmers and Antonio Damasio; Sean Carroll and B. Alan Wallace; Patricia Churchland and Jill Tarter; Rebecca Goldstein and Alan Lightman; Jimena Canales and Paul Davies; Ed Boyden and Mark O’Connell; Elizabeth Kolbert and Siddhartha Mukherjee; Jeremy DeSilva, David Grinspoon, and Tasneem Zehra Husain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSCIENCE / Philosophy & Social Aspects.2bisacsh  aAI.  aBuddhism.  aaliens.  aastrophysics.  aconsciousness.  acyborgs.  aextinction.  aintelligence.  amind-body problem.  aneuroscience.  aphilosophy of mind.  aphysics.  apublic health.  areligion.  atranshumanism.1 aBoyden, Ed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanales, Jimena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarroll, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChalmers, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChurchland, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDamasio, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb